    <!-- INGREDIENT SCIENCE BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>Understanding Cortisol: The HPA Axis, Chronic Stress, and How Adaptogens Intervene</h3>
      <p>Cortisol is not inherently harmful — it is essential for waking up in the morning, responding to physical threats, and regulating blood sugar. The problem is chronic elevation, which occurs when the HPA axis becomes dysregulated and cortisol production fails to return to baseline after a stressor resolves.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Acute Cortisol (Healthy)</strong>
          <p>Cortisol rises in response to a threat, mobilizes glucose, sharpens focus, and suppresses non-essential functions. After the threat resolves, cortisol returns to baseline within 60-90 minutes through negative feedback at the hypothalamus and pituitary. This is normal, healthy stress physiology.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Chronic Cortisol (Harmful)</strong>
          <p>When stressors are constant, cortisol remains elevated and negative feedback mechanisms become blunted. Chronic elevation causes visceral fat gain, muscle catabolism, insulin resistance, immune suppression, hippocampal atrophy (memory impairment), and disrupted sleep architecture through suppressed melatonin production.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Adaptogens (HPA Modulation)</strong>
          <p>Adaptogens like ashwagandha normalize HPA axis sensitivity by modulating cortisol receptor expression and GABAergic signaling in the hypothalamus. They do not suppress cortisol entirely — they restore the appropriate cortisol response curve, allowing healthy acute rises while preventing chronic elevation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Calming Agents (Symptom Relief)</strong>
          <p>GABA, L-theanine, and lemon balm reduce the neurological symptoms of stress (anxiety, racing thoughts, muscle tension) without directly modulating cortisol production. They complement adaptogens by providing immediate relief while the adaptogenic effects build over 4-8 weeks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Optimal cortisol management stack:</strong> The most effective approach combines a clinically dosed adaptogen (KSM-66 ashwagandha 600mg/day) for long-term HPA axis normalization with a calming agent (GABA or L-theanine) for immediate situational stress relief. Take the adaptogen consistently with food; use the calming agent as needed before stressful situations or before bedtime. Allow 60 days for full adaptogenic benefits to manifest.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

