    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Cortisol Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is cortisol and why is it harmful at high levels?</summary>
      <p>Cortisol is a steroid hormone produced by the adrenal glands in response to stress. In acute situations, it is essential for survival — increasing blood sugar, suppressing the immune system, and diverting energy to muscles. However, chronically elevated cortisol causes visceral fat accumulation, muscle breakdown, immune suppression, impaired memory, insulin resistance, and disrupted sleep architecture. A 2017 study in <em>Psychoneuroendocrinology</em> found that chronically elevated cortisol was associated with a 5x increased risk of metabolic syndrome.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can gummies actually lower cortisol levels?</summary>
      <p>Yes. The strongest evidence exists for KSM-66 ashwagandha, which reduced serum cortisol by 27.9% in a 2012 RCT. Rhodiola rosea, phosphatidylserine, and Sensoril ashwagandha also have clinical evidence for cortisol modulation. The key is ingredient quality — patented extracts like KSM-66 and Sensoril have significantly more clinical validation than generic ashwagandha root powder.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is KSM-66 ashwagandha and why does it matter?</summary>
      <p>KSM-66 is a patented, full-spectrum ashwagandha root extract standardized to 5% withanolides — the active compounds responsible for cortisol reduction. It is the most clinically studied ashwagandha extract in the world with 24+ published clinical trials. KSM-66 uses a water-based extraction that preserves the natural balance of withanolides. Generic extracts may vary widely in withanolide content and bioactivity.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for cortisol gummies to work?</summary>
      <p>Adaptogens like ashwagandha typically require 4-8 weeks of consistent daily use. The landmark KSM-66 study measured significant cortisol reduction at 60 days. Some users report subjective stress improvements within 1-2 weeks, but biochemical cortisol changes are gradual. GABA-based formulas may produce faster subjective effects (30-60 minutes) but do not modulate the HPA axis the way adaptogens do.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between adaptogens and calming supplements?</summary>
      <p>Adaptogens (ashwagandha, rhodiola, holy basil) modulate the HPA axis for long-term cortisol normalization over weeks of use. Calming supplements (GABA, L-theanine, lemon balm) work on neurotransmitter systems for rapid, acute relaxation without directly addressing cortisol. The optimal approach combines both: adaptogens for long-term HPA axis modulation and calming agents for immediate situational relief.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can high cortisol cause weight gain?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Chronically elevated cortisol promotes visceral fat accumulation through increased lipoprotein lipase activity, stimulates appetite via neuropeptide Y, and promotes gluconeogenesis (protein-to-glucose conversion). A 2018 study in <em>Obesity Reviews</em> found that cortisol-lowering interventions were associated with modest but significant reductions in waist circumference in chronically stressed adults.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are cortisol gummies safe to take with medication?</summary>
      <p>Ashwagandha can interact with thyroid hormones, immunosuppressants, sedatives, and blood sugar medications. It may increase T3 and T4 thyroid levels and enhance sedative effects. Always consult your physician before combining cortisol gummies with prescription medications, particularly thyroid, autoimmune, or psychiatric medications.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the best time to take cortisol gummies?</summary>
      <p>Cortisol peaks in the morning (6-8 AM) and declines throughout the day. Morning dosing helps modulate the cortisol awakening response; evening dosing supports natural cortisol decline and sleep. Many users split their dose (morning and evening). For GABA-based formulas, take 30-60 minutes before stressful situations or bedtime. Consistency matters more than precise timing for adaptogenic benefits.</p>
    </details>

